WEBVTT

00:59.434 --> 01:01.019
<i>How often do you come to Brooklyn?</i>

01:01.102 --> 01:02.937
Honestly, the only time
I come to Brooklyn

01:03.021 --> 01:05.065
-is to eat at this neighborhood.

01:05.148 --> 01:10.111
Frankies, Pok Pok,
and if the line is not too long, Lucali's.

01:10.195 --> 01:12.947
But the main reason I come
is to eat at Lucali's.

01:15.617 --> 01:18.453
<i>My favorite time to come here</i>
<i>is the summer or spring,</i>

01:18.536 --> 01:20.371
when you can bring your own beer,

01:20.455 --> 01:22.540
if the line's long,
you put your name down...

01:22.624 --> 01:24.292
<i> You hang out.</i>
<i>-Hang out.</i>

01:24.375 --> 01:29.172
Sometimes I get a couple spicy tuna rolls
at the sushi place on the corner.

01:29.255 --> 01:31.049
Really?
When I first opened,

01:37.013 --> 01:41.643
I made the dough one night
and I didn't put enough water in it.

01:41.726 --> 01:42.560
I couldn't stretch it.

01:43.520 --> 01:45.814
So, I called my brother.
He lives right around the block.

01:45.897 --> 01:48.233
I was like, "Yo, bring
Grandma's rolling pin in here."

01:48.316 --> 01:51.069
The line was crazy
and I couldn't make pizza.

01:51.152 --> 01:53.321
He took too long.
I just grabbed a wine bottle,

01:53.404 --> 01:55.532
started doing it,
the pizzas came out better.

01:56.157 --> 01:59.619
<i>When you roll it,</i>
<i>you get more of a flat, crispier pie.</i>

02:00.245 --> 02:02.205
How did you end up
with that dough?

02:02.288 --> 02:03.248
It's what I made.

02:04.249 --> 02:06.292
You know, it's like I says,
I thought, "Yeah, it's dough."

02:06.376 --> 02:09.629
I didn't know
the whole process and everything.

02:15.093 --> 02:17.470
<i>In the kitchen,</i>
<i>I love the camaraderie</i>

02:17.554 --> 02:19.389
<i>of being able to work with other people.</i>

02:19.472 --> 02:22.684
<i>I looked at it as this band of outsiders.</i>

02:22.767 --> 02:26.437
One reason why I got into food
was because it was exactly that.

02:26.521 --> 02:31.359
<i>It was, I guess, a form of rebellion</i>
<i>and badass,</i>

02:31.442 --> 02:33.611
<i>right, and badass through your food...</i>

02:33.695 --> 02:36.698
<i>That had this crazy dichotomy</i>
<i>of personality</i>

02:36.781 --> 02:40.451
where they could barely take care
of themselves outside the kitchen,

02:40.535 --> 02:43.913
but inside the kitchen,
they were like special forces,

02:43.997 --> 02:45.248
highly trained assassins.

02:45.331 --> 02:48.334
A little light on the sauce,
but other than that...

02:48.418 --> 02:50.503
-I thought it was good on the sauce.
-Eh.

02:51.170 --> 02:54.132
<i>So why pizza</i>

02:54.716 --> 02:55.925
<i>Growing up as a kid, I was like,</i>

02:56.009 --> 02:58.261
<i>"If I was making pizza,</i>
<i>I'd do it this way."</i>

02:58.970 --> 03:02.515
<i>A friend of mine opened a pizzeria.</i>
<i>I` said, "I wanna try making a pie,"</i>

03:02.599 --> 03:04.392
<i>and, like, I did it my way.</i>

03:04.475 --> 03:07.228
<i>And, he was like,</i>
<i>"Wow, that's a pretty good pizza."</i>

03:09.564 --> 03:13.860
Mark Iacono in Lucali,
I went to it when it was not open yet.

03:13.943 --> 03:16.946
It's part of his shtick
that they're not fully open.

03:17.447 --> 03:19.908
<i>And hearing the story of growing up there,</i>
<i>in the candy shop,</i>

03:19.991 --> 03:22.493
<i>and he'd gone there when it was closing.</i>

03:22.577 --> 03:25.538
<i>He couldn't bear to see that, </i>
<i>so he left his job as a marble cutter</i>

03:25.622 --> 03:28.291
<i>to open this pizzeria</i>
<i>for his neighborhood.</i>

03:30.960 --> 03:32.295
See the difference
when you cook it slow?

03:32.378 --> 03:33.212
Wow. Totally.

03:34.047 --> 03:35.632
This is my favorite pie.

03:36.799 --> 03:38.801
-I tell everyone.
-This, as far as my pie,

03:38.885 --> 03:40.053
-or just--
-This is my favorite pizza.

03:40.136 --> 03:42.764
I voted for this on the top 50
restaurants in the world.

03:42.847 --> 03:44.849
-Again. Yeah!
Thank you.

03:44.933 --> 03:47.060
You would wish that on him?
He's such a nice man.

03:47.143 --> 03:50.480
I have to be truthful.
-I'm here just making pies,

03:50.563 --> 03:53.358
I don't even pay attention
to what goes on out there.

03:53.441 --> 03:56.444
But then it's a debate of
what is actually pizza?

03:56.527 --> 03:59.822
If we were in Naples,
would they consider this pizza?

04:00.907 --> 04:02.200
-I can care less what they consider.
-Thank you.

04:02.283 --> 04:05.578
Right. What if you put barbecue chicken
and cilantro on top of it?

04:05.662 --> 04:07.622
You've had a barbecue chicken pizza
in your day.

04:07.705 --> 04:08.831
No, I haven't.

04:08.915 --> 04:10.875
I stick to the traditional
New York toppings.

04:10.959 --> 04:12.627
Here--
-I try to do them really well.

04:12.710 --> 04:15.546
Is there, so... Where is the outer limit
of toppings for you?

04:15.630 --> 04:17.382
You can throw ramen on top of pizza dough.

04:17.465 --> 04:18.549
-Please, don't.

04:18.633 --> 04:19.634
Nah.  What is that?

04:30.144 --> 04:31.980
This is Maguro tuna.

04:33.856 --> 04:35.441
Hmm.

04:37.735 --> 04:39.445
Wow.

04:39.529 --> 04:42.949
Please just
separate it a little like this and try it.

04:43.032 --> 04:45.243
A little wasabi and soy sauce.

04:45.326 --> 04:48.329
Oh, we're gonna get
destroyed with food, aren't we?

04:49.247 --> 04:50.206
Delicious.

04:50.790 --> 04:52.875
You want a fork?
No.

04:54.002 --> 04:56.754
That was mean.
That was mean of me, Aziz, I'm sorry.

04:56.838 --> 04:58.047
Uh, please come here.

04:58.881 --> 05:01.342
What is going on?
Where did you come from?

05:03.636 --> 05:06.139
I dunno what's happening.
We're supposed to be talking about pizza.

05:06.222 --> 05:07.890
That's right. That's right.

05:07.974 --> 05:09.100
That's a Japanese tip.

05:09.183 --> 05:12.645
If you don't know what's going on,
you just say...

05:13.229 --> 05:16.482
We're going
to surprise you, Chang-san.

05:16.566 --> 05:18.568
Maybe life
is a computer simulation.

05:18.651 --> 05:21.612
-This is us<i> Vanilla Sky</i>-ing ourselves.

05:21.696 --> 05:25.825
First, please eat
this meaty red tuna with white vinegar.

05:25.908 --> 05:27.994
He wants you to--
I am perplexed.

05:28.077 --> 05:29.454
What does he wanna make with this?

05:29.537 --> 05:31.247
I'll be making pizza with this.

05:31.331 --> 05:32.165
Pizza?

05:32.248 --> 05:33.499
Yes, pizza.

05:33.583 --> 05:36.294
I used to make
a tuna-wasabi pizza, believe it or not.

05:36.377 --> 05:38.963
Wow.
-At The Mercer Kitchen.

05:39.047 --> 05:40.131
I don't even, I'm not going--

05:40.214 --> 05:41.966
I thought that was about
some dark days at CPK.

05:42.050 --> 05:44.719
-Yeah.
-California Pizza Kitchens.

05:45.303 --> 05:47.013
Every day,

05:47.096 --> 05:49.724
the taste of tuna from the Japanese sea
can change every day.

05:49.807 --> 05:51.726
Can we get to the pizza though?

05:53.102 --> 05:54.520
All right, let's cook the pizza.

06:03.321 --> 06:05.573
<i>So the pizza we're</i>
<i>about to have is all Japanese.</i>

06:05.656 --> 06:07.533
<i>Every element is from Japan.</i>

06:18.419 --> 06:22.507
Now what else is special
about this pizza isn't the tomato sauce.

06:22.590 --> 06:23.841
It's mayonnaise.

06:23.925 --> 06:24.801
Mayonnaise?

06:26.052 --> 06:28.221
What?

06:28.304 --> 06:31.140
What's going on?

06:31.224 --> 06:34.936
The sauce
is original mayonnaise and, uh, corn.

06:35.019 --> 06:36.062
Corn?

06:36.145 --> 06:38.022
Pizza, but sushi.

06:38.940 --> 06:45.238
This is this one. This is this one.
Please, together.

06:45.321 --> 06:47.532
Oh, my God,
that's fucking delicious.

06:47.615 --> 06:50.076
A lot of wasabi, okay?

06:53.496 --> 06:56.415
I didn't even know, like,
that you had this stuff.

06:56.499 --> 07:00.086
But I also understand, that this is
a very different Japanese mentality

07:00.169 --> 07:02.922
-of you wanting to do more, different.
-Yes, I know.

07:03.005 --> 07:06.092
I don't like fusion. Separate.

07:06.759 --> 07:09.303
How you can say that's not fusion...

07:09.387 --> 07:11.055
Wait, what's happening?

07:11.139 --> 07:13.266
I really don't consider this fusion.

07:13.349 --> 07:15.560
This uses Japanese ingredients.

07:16.394 --> 07:19.897
I like this. Very Donald Trump of you.
Alternative facts.

07:21.649 --> 07:23.192
The reason he combined this is

07:23.276 --> 07:25.528
'cause it's, like, for you,
you're eating sushi.

07:25.611 --> 07:26.612
Yeah.

07:26.696 --> 07:32.410
When I thought about how
to eat tasty tuna on a delicious pizza,

07:32.493 --> 07:34.245
I thought about sushi
and made it that way.

07:34.829 --> 07:38.332
You realize that every pizza
is a living thing. Each one is different.

07:38.416 --> 07:39.250
Yes.

07:39.959 --> 07:42.545
Like snowflakes. But you can eat them.

07:48.593 --> 07:50.386
<i>Can we just draw</i>
<i>the line right now?</i>

07:50.470 --> 07:51.304
<i>So you--</i>

07:51.387 --> 07:52.555
For all of America...

07:52.638 --> 07:55.558
It's that sauce and cheese.
Sauce and cheese and dough.

07:55.641 --> 07:57.977
Let's nip it in the bud.
I'm tired of the arguing.

07:58.060 --> 07:59.437
So let's just say this.

07:59.520 --> 08:04.358
Anything else that's not sauce and cheese
is flatbread.

08:04.442 --> 08:06.110
Yeah.
What about for you?

08:06.194 --> 08:08.779
The first time you ever made me a pizza,
it had mapo tofu on it.

08:08.863 --> 08:11.657
-It did. It was delicious.
-It was delicious.

08:11.741 --> 08:13.075
I know you'll say
it's not a pizza,

08:13.159 --> 08:16.329
but one of those places that put
salad on a pizza. They cook the dough...

08:16.412 --> 08:18.414
Seems like a great thing
to eat salad on top of.

08:18.498 --> 08:21.250
When you say salad, are you talking
about arugula sprinkled on the...

08:22.919 --> 08:25.254
How about Chicago?
Have you done Chicago

08:25.338 --> 08:26.297
I like it.

08:26.380 --> 08:27.256
-Yeah.

08:27.340 --> 08:28.549
-Yeah.

08:28.633 --> 08:31.761
It's a casserole in a baked edible crust.

08:33.137 --> 08:37.183
I think New Haven pizza, as a community,
has the best pizza in America.

08:37.266 --> 08:38.518
Have you spent time up there--

08:38.601 --> 08:40.478
-I still have not made it there.
Oh, my gosh.

08:40.561 --> 08:44.482
It's a surprising statement.
I understand, but you gotta check it out.

08:44.565 --> 08:48.110
You know what? All right.
I'll take your word for it.

09:00.164 --> 09:02.375
<i>Good morning,</i>
<i>ladies and gentlemen,</i>

09:02.458 --> 09:03.918
<i>welcome aboard the...</i>

09:04.001 --> 09:06.837
<i>Brooklyn was an amazing place</i>
<i>to grow up.</i>

09:06.921 --> 09:08.548
<i>There was just so much to do.</i>

09:08.631 --> 09:11.592
<i>It was very adventurous,</i>
<i>believe it or not.</i>

09:11.676 --> 09:15.388
As a young kid, going into all
the neighborhoods, it was like <i>Tom Sawyer.</i>

09:15.471 --> 09:16.847
Like we were running away from home.

09:18.266 --> 09:21.811
<i>I'm so closed-minded, you know,</i>
<i>New York, New York, New York.</i>

09:21.894 --> 09:27.692
<i>A lot of people recommend pizzerias to me</i>
<i>and, for the most part, they fall short.</i>

09:27.775 --> 09:30.861
So now I'm a little leery
about making these trips.

09:31.988 --> 09:35.032
<i>I gotta step up my pizza game, my travels.</i>

09:36.742 --> 09:39.787
<i>When people speak of Connecticut pizza,</i>

09:39.870 --> 09:43.457
<i>they only mention two places:</i>
<i>Pepe's and Sally's.</i>

09:46.502 --> 09:48.963
My grandfather, he had this headdress,

09:49.046 --> 09:50.798
and he would have his pizzas
on his headdress,

09:50.881 --> 09:52.925
and he would go around selling his pizzas.

09:53.009 --> 09:55.052
Wait, he'd transport pizzas on his head?

09:55.136 --> 09:56.846
-On his head, yeah.

09:57.722 --> 10:00.600
<i>My grandfather</i>
<i>was the first one in New Haven</i>

10:00.683 --> 10:03.936
<i>to have a dine-in pizza restaurant.</i>
<i>Frank Pepe's.</i>

10:05.605 --> 10:08.190
-This is a coal fire.
Yep.

10:08.274 --> 10:10.735
This is open hearth.
It's all open inside.

10:10.818 --> 10:13.529
Wow.
-This oven was actually a bread baker.

10:13.613 --> 10:15.114
This was a bread oven?
-Right.

10:15.948 --> 10:17.408
-You could fit a lot of pizzas in there.
-Oh, yeah.

10:18.868 --> 10:20.369
-We're gonna make some pizza.

10:20.453 --> 10:23.831
All right. It looks like you guys
use a really wet dough.

10:23.914 --> 10:27.293
It is. My grandfather, back in the day,
he never had refrigeration.

10:27.376 --> 10:29.420
<i>Right.</i>
<i>-So the dough was out all the time.</i>

10:29.503 --> 10:31.297
<i>I love the rustic look of it.</i>

10:31.380 --> 10:34.675
It's not cookie-cutter perfect.
-It shouldn't be.

10:34.759 --> 10:36.302
