15:16.165 --> 15:18.876
Right? I would rather eat this
than Neapolitan style, so...

15:18.959 --> 15:20.336
Just because it's from Italy

15:20.419 --> 15:22.379
-doesn't mean it's better.
-Thank you.

15:22.963 --> 15:25.174
And that's what I say about pizza.

15:26.759 --> 15:30.220
They invented it,
we Italian-Americans perfected it.

15:39.355 --> 15:41.941
I am Antonio Pace.

15:42.691 --> 15:45.611
The President of
the Association Verace Pizza Napoletana.

15:47.696 --> 15:52.201
<i>Our association was founded</i>
<i>32 years ago with a specific purpose:</i>

15:52.284 --> 15:56.121
<i>Guaranteeing the authority of pizza</i>
<i>to the City of Naples.</i>

15:56.205 --> 16:00.751
And to spread all over the world
the right way to make a Neapolitan pizza.

16:03.087 --> 16:06.757
<i>For us, Neapolitan pizza</i>
<i>is a philosophy of life.</i>

16:08.509 --> 16:13.263
When we were making pizzas,
you were still fighting with Indians.

16:39.373 --> 16:41.250
So, you've been to Italy before?
Never in Naples.

16:41.333 --> 16:42.334
Never in Naples.

16:42.418 --> 16:43.961
It's this way.

16:45.337 --> 16:46.922
We're in the back streets of Naples.

16:47.006 --> 16:48.257
-I love this.
I know.

16:48.340 --> 16:50.718
I can't quite get over how pretty it is.

16:51.844 --> 16:54.304
I feel like there's an almost obsession

16:54.388 --> 16:58.809
with the idea of Neapolitan pizza
being the first pizza

16:58.892 --> 17:00.185
or the place that pizza comes from.

17:00.269 --> 17:01.854
-It's a romantic story.
-Yeah.

17:01.937 --> 17:06.400
<i>I don't buy so deeply into the idea </i>
<i>of bread topped with things </i>

17:06.483 --> 17:09.695
came from one place, one time.

17:10.279 --> 17:13.490
I feel as soon as humans figured out
how to mix wheat and water,

17:13.574 --> 17:15.701
they probably started putting shit on it
to try to make it taste better.

17:16.577 --> 17:18.579
<i>But it is their culture.</i>
<i>Right.</i>

17:18.662 --> 17:20.414
<i>So, I guess</i>
<i>we have to respect it.</i>

17:20.497 --> 17:25.210
Wish I'd taken the line of respecting it,
but now I'm the asshole criticizing it.

17:25.878 --> 17:27.171
Look at this.

17:27.254 --> 17:29.757
-Look at these.
-They look like heirlooms.

17:32.968 --> 17:35.429
Give me one basket.
One basket?

17:35.512 --> 17:37.556
Yeah, and two of these.

17:37.639 --> 17:38.891
-No. Two, no.

17:38.974 --> 17:40.976
Two basket.
It's a particular tomato.

17:41.060 --> 17:42.853
-All right, two baskets.
-Yeah.

17:44.563 --> 17:50.778
<i>Our region made tomatoes</i>
<i>an element of gastronomic culture.</i>

17:50.861 --> 17:53.947
So San Marzano tomato is the ideal one.

17:56.366 --> 18:01.080
The Neapolitan pizza came together
in its glorious state

18:01.163 --> 18:05.876
with the use of tomato as food.

18:08.003 --> 18:11.507
<i>That is </i>
<i>the mark of Verace Pizza Napoletana.</i>

18:11.590 --> 18:15.552
It certifies the quality of our pizza.

18:19.264 --> 18:23.393
That mark certifies
that our product is made with

18:23.477 --> 18:26.188
mozzarella fior di latte Campana.

18:26.271 --> 18:28.816
Our dough is made according to regulation.

18:28.899 --> 18:31.777
It looks super wet.
Yes, very delicate.

18:31.860 --> 18:35.489
You just need
3 or 4 ingredients for Neapolitan pizza.

18:38.784 --> 18:41.620
Those are the tomatoes
you bought across the street.

18:41.703 --> 18:44.706
This is classic Margherita.

18:44.790 --> 18:46.667
-Parmigiano.
Parmigiano<i>.</i>

18:46.750 --> 18:48.127
Makes everything delicious.

18:48.210 --> 18:51.797
Is it okay to put parmesan cheese
on a Neapolitan pizza?

18:52.381 --> 18:54.383
In every pizza, parmesan, yes.

18:55.592 --> 18:57.427
<i>How long does it take</i>
<i>you to cook a pizza?</i>

18:57.511 --> 19:00.889
<i>50 or 60 seconds.</i>

19:00.973 --> 19:02.724
<i>Wow, that's fast.</i>
<i>That's fast.</i>

19:06.353 --> 19:09.022
Wow. Just like that.

19:12.151 --> 19:15.988
We start a visual check.

19:16.071 --> 19:18.657
The first thing is breaking the crust

19:18.740 --> 19:21.285
and see if inside
there is an alveolar structure.

19:21.368 --> 19:25.038
In this case, the pizza has fairly risen.

19:26.915 --> 19:29.042
We're about to eat
our first pizza in Naples.

19:29.126 --> 19:34.173
Then we should smell it,
even if it is not really polite.

19:34.256 --> 19:40.846
The smell of the crust
should be a fragrance of fresh bread,

19:41.471 --> 19:43.682
without strong smell of yeast.

19:46.768 --> 19:49.897
So, if you smell the yeast
or the fermentation, it's no good?

19:49.980 --> 19:52.774
Right! If it has
a sour smell, it is not good.

19:52.858 --> 19:58.280
The way to eat pizza
is fold it like a wallet.

19:58.363 --> 20:04.453
After the first bite, you feel
the dough melt in your mouth.

20:05.204 --> 20:07.247
I love the pizza.
I'm very into this.

20:07.331 --> 20:11.376
I tried a lot of Neapolitan pizza.
I've never had anything this good.

20:14.588 --> 20:15.505
Maybe we should get another pie?

20:15.589 --> 20:16.965
-Yeah.

20:17.049 --> 20:18.133
All right, great.

20:18.217 --> 20:19.635
Can we get one more?

20:26.183 --> 20:31.480
<i>♪ Pizza, I'm in love with pizza ♪</i>

20:31.563 --> 20:34.233
<i>♪ All I think is pizza ♪</i>

20:34.316 --> 20:38.028
<i>♪ A piece of pizza ♪</i>

20:38.111 --> 20:41.114
<i>♪ And I don't care what they say ♪</i>

20:41.198 --> 20:43.659
<i>♪ I'm gonna eat it anyway ♪</i>

20:43.742 --> 20:47.246
<i>♪ 'Cause it's pizza ♪</i>

21:04.680 --> 21:06.515
<i>Superstar celebrity chef</i>
<i>Wolfgang Puck.</i>

21:06.598 --> 21:08.976
<i>Now, he has restaurants</i>
<i>all over the world.</i>

21:09.518 --> 21:13.146
This guy is crazy successful.
He is such a mogul.

21:15.732 --> 21:18.568
-Oh, my God!
-Hi, Chef.

21:18.652 --> 21:19.820
How are you?
-Sorry, I'm so late.

21:19.903 --> 21:23.573
We can make pizza at midnight,
for breakfast, anytime.

21:25.242 --> 21:27.286
You don't make pizza yet
in your restaurant?

21:27.369 --> 21:28.495
No.

21:28.578 --> 21:32.582
I want to, but I think a lot of my friends
would be upset at me.

21:32.666 --> 21:36.169
You know how upset they were at me.
They say, "An Austrian making pizza?

21:36.253 --> 21:37.671
What the heck?"

21:37.754 --> 21:44.177
If we wanna make pizza the way they did
in Naples 300 years ago, it's okay.

21:44.261 --> 21:48.515
I'm not saying it's not good or whatever,
but it's just not our style.

21:48.598 --> 21:52.144
So, do you think authenticity
is overrated in certain things?

21:52.227 --> 21:55.605
Authenticity, I love it
when you go to a place.

21:55.689 --> 21:58.525
You know, when I'm in Italy,
I wanna taste Italian food.

21:58.608 --> 22:01.903
But America is a melting pot of cultures.

22:01.987 --> 22:06.533
So, I think there's nothing wrong with
melting some of the cuisines together.

22:06.616 --> 22:10.245
So, in the old times,
there was a guy named Johnny Carson.

22:10.329 --> 22:13.165
-He was what Jimmy Fallon does today.
-Yeah.

22:13.248 --> 22:16.335
-I'm not that young.
-Okay.

22:16.418 --> 22:18.628
-I remember Johnny Carson's last episode.

22:19.588 --> 22:21.590
Little something here, it's nice.

22:21.673 --> 22:22.966
Can I try it, if you like?

22:23.050 --> 22:25.552
Please sit down,
and we'll give you a Pinacolonic.

22:27.262 --> 22:29.306
<i>Johnny Carson used to</i>
<i>come on Friday nights</i>

22:29.389 --> 22:30.849
<i>and order 10, 12 pizzas to go.</i>

22:30.932 --> 22:32.476
Sit in the sun today?

22:32.559 --> 22:36.605
-We're going to Spago.
-Spago!

22:36.688 --> 22:38.398
<i>After the third or fourth time,</i>
<i>I said, </i>

22:38.482 --> 22:40.317
"Johnny, you're having
another pizza party."

22:40.400 --> 22:42.402
He says, "No, I put them in my freezer."

22:42.486 --> 22:45.447
I said, "What the hell?
You put my pizzas in the freezer?

22:45.530 --> 22:46.823
I'm not gonna make
pizzas anymore for you."

22:46.907 --> 22:49.951
He says, "No, it's as good
as the regular one here."

22:50.035 --> 22:52.704
I said, "Yeah, yeah, yeah."
I was so upset.

22:52.788 --> 22:56.875
Finally, I tried it myself,
and I said, "You know what?

22:56.958 --> 23:00.337
Maybe it's not quite as good as ours
we have at Spago, but it's pretty good."

23:00.420 --> 23:03.215
<i>So, we started doing...</i>
<i>-Johnny Carson is behind...</i>

23:03.298 --> 23:04.758
<i>Behind the frozen pizzas. </i>

23:04.841 --> 23:09.387
But he didn't sign a deal with me
so he didn't get any royalties, thank God.

23:09.471 --> 23:12.099
Let's do our smoked salmon pizza.
-I wanna see that.

23:12.182 --> 23:13.517
Yeah.

23:13.600 --> 23:17.437
You think we've lost craftsmanship though?
If we're sacrificing creativity?

23:17.521 --> 23:21.108
Creativity is good by somebody
who is a good craftsman.

23:21.191 --> 23:25.779
If you know the basics,
if you know your profession really well,

23:25.862 --> 23:29.116
then you can navigate
and try other things.

23:29.199 --> 23:32.160
If you were from Italy,
there is no way you could have done this.

23:32.244 --> 23:33.411
I know.

23:33.495 --> 23:35.330
Because you're an outsider,
you're allowed to do this.

23:35.413 --> 23:36.289
Exactly.

23:36.373 --> 23:39.626
My Italian friends would have come
and said, "What the heck is that?"

23:40.585 --> 23:43.547
You have to put a little caviar on top.

23:44.422 --> 23:48.343
But it makes people upset
when you change and challenge convention.

23:48.426 --> 23:51.304
You know, people hate change.

23:51.388 --> 23:54.015
-No.

23:54.099 --> 23:57.269
-As long as I live, I always will do that.

23:57.352 --> 23:59.229
And at the end of the day,

23:59.312 --> 24:02.065
as long as you get
enough other people to come

24:02.149 --> 24:05.068
who'll say, "Wow! This is
really interesting," it's fine.

24:05.152 --> 24:06.903
I mean, just talking to you now,
I'm like,

24:06.987 --> 24:09.072
"Oh, my gosh!
There's so many similarities."

24:09.156 --> 24:11.950
Part of it is
there's a rebellious streak in you. Right?

24:12.033 --> 24:13.493
Yeah. No, totally.

24:13.577 --> 24:17.038
Still today, still today, I think,

24:17.122 --> 24:20.917
in a way, for me, I'm more like
the coach now than the player.

24:21.001 --> 24:22.043
No matter how good you are,

24:22.127 --> 24:26.840
you won't wanna play basketball
when you're 45 or 48 or 50 years old.

24:26.923 --> 24:28.675
I use the same analogy for myself
all the time.

24:28.758 --> 24:29.593
Yeah?

24:29.676 --> 24:33.388
Yeah. I can't believe it.
I'm a Korean-American version of you.

24:33.471 --> 24:34.306
Really?

24:38.602 --> 24:40.520
<i>Pizza is a disk of dough.</i>

24:40.604 --> 24:42.981
<i>Toppings must be picked</i>
<i>with a gastronomic culture</i>

24:43.064 --> 24:45.066
and sense of taste.

24:46.234 --> 24:48.862
<i>When we wrote our guidelines,</i>

24:48.945 --> 24:51.698
<i>fior di latte cheese was having a decline.</i>

24:51.781 --> 24:56.203
That's why I,
when I wrote the first guidelines,

24:56.286 --> 24:58.663
I added buffalo mozzarella as an option.

25:07.589 --> 25:12.344
Wow! What makes
the buffalo milk from Campania so special?

25:12.427 --> 25:15.931
In Campania,
we started breeding buffaloes

25:16.014 --> 25:19.142
around the years 1000-1100.

25:19.226 --> 25:20.852
In 1000 A.D.?

25:20.936 --> 25:21.811
Yes.

25:21.895 --> 25:24.773
<i>The animals came from</i>
<i>Northern Africa and Asia,</i>

25:24.856 --> 25:27.567
<i>brought to Italy by the Normans.</i>

25:33.198 --> 25:36.409
<i>We are those who know</i>
<i>how to make the real mozzarella di bufala.</i>

25:36.993 --> 25:41.581
There are good industries, of course,

25:41.665 --> 25:44.584
but artisans have something more.

25:49.547 --> 25:51.508
-Okay.

25:51.591 --> 25:53.009
All right.

25:55.220 --> 25:56.721
Don't fold.
-I'm trying.

25:57.305 --> 25:59.724
<i>Around the year 1000,</i>

25:59.808 --> 26:02.811
<i>the monastery of Capua</i>

26:02.894 --> 26:08.650
<i>tried to curdle their milk</i>

26:08.733 --> 26:11.611
<i>and make cheese.</i>

26:11.695 --> 26:13.905
<i>They tried to cook it</i>

26:13.989 --> 26:19.536
<i>and noticed that it started straining.</i>

26:19.619 --> 26:26.084
<i>And they found that the product was tasty.</i>

26:28.336 --> 26:30.922
Easy, just twist it up
into a perfect braid.

26:31.006 --> 26:32.173
Go for it.

26:32.257 --> 26:33.842
I think I'm gonna
leave that to the professionals.

26:38.138 --> 26:41.558
Authenticity, in terms of storytelling,
is important to me,

26:41.641 --> 26:45.770
but authenticity in food is not a thing.

26:45.854 --> 26:48.940
And it's like, whoever gave you
that authentic food experience,

26:49.024 --> 26:51.484
probably has never thought
about themselves as authentic.

26:52.694 --> 26:56.698
<i>There's a reductive quality</i>
<i>to saying that something's authentic.</i>

27:09.085 --> 27:10.086
<i>Some things become special</i>

27:10.170 --> 27:12.464
<i>when you try and find your own way.</i>

27:12.547 --> 27:17.010
<i>The starting point</i>
<i>was to do something authentic</i>

27:17.093 --> 27:19.596
<i>by not trying to be authentic.</i>

27:19.679 --> 27:23.350
<i>I think that's a big flaw</i>
<i>in the world of pizza, particularly.</i>

27:23.433 --> 27:24.642
That is the most Italian thing,

27:24.726 --> 27:26.936
but if you only look at
how it used to be done,

27:27.020 --> 27:28.980
or how it's supposed to be done,

27:29.064 --> 27:30.565
you don't allow yourself
to move it forward.

27:31.232 --> 27:34.027
<i>If you do an authentic Neapolitan pizza,</i>

27:34.110 --> 27:38.365
you must import buffalo mozzarella
from the Campania region.

27:38.448 --> 27:40.408
-Now, who makes these rules...

27:40.492 --> 27:44.788
...has an obvious interest
in the export of buffalo mozzarella.

27:45.830 --> 27:49.542
So, how is it that you can be told
that freshness is everything?

27:49.626 --> 27:52.337
That in Naples, they say
you have 24 different mozzarellas

27:52.420 --> 27:54.672
for every hour after it's been produced.

27:54.756 --> 27:56.007
But you still
you need to buy it in import,

27:56.091 --> 27:57.675
and it's gonna take you seven days
to get it to Copenhagen.

27:57.759 --> 27:59.052
It didn't make sense to me.

27:59.636 --> 28:02.347
<i>If I need freshness,</i>
<i>we'll need to make it ourselves.</i>

28:02.430 --> 28:03.264
<i> You taught yourself</i>
<i>how to make it?</i>

28:05.225 --> 28:06.851
-Amazing.
-A lot of YouTube,

28:06.935 --> 28:10.522
<i>a lot of research, a lot of experimenting,</i>
<i>a lot of shit mozzarella.</i>

28:10.605 --> 28:13.024
Then, last year, we got cows.

28:16.986 --> 28:19.572
<i>We got our own milk</i>
<i>from our own herd of Jersey cows.</i>

28:20.156 --> 28:21.950
The mozzarella just...

28:22.033 --> 28:23.993
Like magical dust on it.

28:24.077 --> 28:24.911
<i>It was crazy.</i>

28:26.204 --> 28:27.872
<i>Much, much better.</i>

28:27.956 --> 28:30.792
-You're a big-ass dreamer.
-Yeah, I am.

28:30.875 --> 28:32.460
That's what I've always admired about you.

28:32.544 --> 28:34.421
<i>You just fucking go for it.</i>

28:34.504 --> 28:37.966
<i>I always make fun of my friends</i>
<i>that are Italian chefs that</i>

28:38.049 --> 28:39.884
you can't fuck with
anything that's Italian.

28:39.968 --> 28:42.178
And that tradition,

28:42.262 --> 28:46.182
that, like, fear of doing
something that is not really Italian,

28:46.266 --> 28:49.352
which, as an immigrant, for me
was a big deal.

28:49.436 --> 28:52.021
<i>I so wanted to be Italian,</i>
<i>wanted to feel Italian.</i>

28:52.105 --> 28:55.650
I want... I was like, "You know what?
I'm mixed. My mom is Norwegian.

28:55.734 --> 28:57.652
-I'm born in Italy, my father is Italian."
-Yeah.

28:57.736 --> 28:58.903
I'm a big mix. I don't care.

28:59.738 --> 29:02.198
<i>This idea of </i>
<i>everything is in a certain way</i>

29:02.282 --> 29:03.533
<i>and it should be kept that way,</i>

29:03.616 --> 29:07.620
has really been, like,
provoking me to tinker,

29:07.704 --> 29:10.331
<i>to say, "I think this can be done better."</i>

29:12.876 --> 29:16.755
I hate being on camera, and being like,
"Oh, that's so delicious." I'm like...

29:16.838 --> 29:18.590
'cause it seems so lame,

29:18.673 --> 29:20.759
-but it's fucking delicious.
-Right.

29:24.095 --> 29:26.055
<i>Our pizza is sourdough-based.</i> <i>Like, the traditional pizza is on yeast,</i>

29:28.183 --> 29:31.186
and it is a fast fermentation,
it's a fast food.

29:31.269 --> 29:34.773
If you do a real Neapolitan pizza,
you will probably have

29:34.856 --> 29:36.691
the outside, the crust on it, be bigger...

29:36.775 --> 29:38.109
-More bubbles.
-...more open. Yeah.

29:38.193 --> 29:40.236
But what I think is a huge factor is

29:40.320 --> 29:44.574
when you open this, if you smell this,
it doesn't smell of yeast.

29:44.657 --> 29:48.203
And there is no pizza that has yeast in it
where you cannot smell the yeast.

29:48.286 --> 29:51.831
And for me, it's like, you put a...
you put a cap on it.

29:51.915 --> 29:55.084
It's not possible to, flavor-wise,
develop something that is not that thing.

29:55.168 --> 29:57.420
It's funny to me
because Italians should be

29:57.504 --> 30:00.590
proponents of the sourdough method,
and not the yeast method.

30:00.673 --> 30:02.509
-That doesn't make sense.
-Yeah.

30:03.092 --> 30:06.054
But in that trade-off
between flavor and texture,

30:06.137 --> 30:07.889
this is our choice.

30:09.516 --> 30:12.811
Think about all
the bad Italian restaurants in America.

30:12.894 --> 30:14.187
Yeah.
-Think about

30:14.270 --> 30:17.482
all the restaurants that open up
in New York City to this day.

30:17.565 --> 30:18.691
How many are Italian?

30:19.275 --> 30:21.486
Just, Italian never goes out of style.

30:21.569 --> 30:25.406
I think that Italian-American food
is a source of anger for you.

30:25.490 --> 30:26.825
You're jealous of the success...

30:26.908 --> 30:29.118
-Yes. Jealous.
-...and acceptance

30:29.202 --> 30:32.121
that Italian-American cuisine
receives in America.

30:32.205 --> 30:36.584
And it's not really anger,
it's just sort of rage that, uh...

30:37.335 --> 30:40.964
I don't understand why Italian food,
Italian-American food,

30:41.047 --> 30:43.174
is so beloved in this country,

30:43.258 --> 30:45.093
-more than anything else.

30:45.176 --> 30:46.970
-Of course I've had it.
-It's very delicious.

30:47.053 --> 30:49.722
What about bad pizza?
What about Domino's Pizza?

30:49.806 --> 30:51.015
Did you ever have...

30:51.099 --> 30:54.644
I grew up in the suburbs
and Domino's was the pizza of my youth.

30:54.727 --> 30:56.980
It's good.
It's pretty good right now.

30:57.063 --> 30:58.064
What?

30:58.147 --> 30:59.816
-Not the one I had. Is it because
you know more about pizza now?

31:01.651 --> 31:03.778
No, no. I was really, really disappointed.

31:03.862 --> 31:05.446
Don't be upset at me.

31:05.530 --> 31:07.866
No, I'm not.
-But I order Domino's,

31:07.949 --> 31:11.202
you know, occasionally,
once a couple of months.

31:11.286 --> 31:12.787
I'll send you pies more often.

31:18.167 --> 31:20.003
Delivery.

31:20.587 --> 31:22.463
What do you want on your pizza, man?

31:22.547 --> 31:23.590
Why don't you get--
-Get a plain pie.

31:23.673 --> 31:26.342
You get a plain pie and then
make one of your insane creations.

31:26.426 --> 31:27.260
Don't be jerks.

31:27.343 --> 31:28.845
We'll wait till the pizza's here
to be jerks.

31:28.928 --> 31:31.139
Do you want hand-tossed,
thin crust, Brooklyn style?

31:31.222 --> 31:32.515
